The Lagos State Government (LASG) will continue dislodgement of illegal slabs across the state. In line with this, the government said most of the approved abattoir projects have been completed except that of Lagos Island located on Simpson Street. Head, Monitoring, Enforcement and Compliance (MEC) Team, Ministry of Agriculture, Gbolabo Kehinde said the one on Lagos Island will be completed in the few months. He   encouraged operators of illegal slabs in Lagos Island to patronise abattoirs  near to them. He said rehabilitation works have been undertaken in the 20 approved slaughter slabs in the state in a bid to improve their present states to meet international standards . Some of the approved abattoirs include Matori, Itire, Oko-Oba Abattoirs and Lairage, Agege; Achakpo, Ajegunle; Epe and Ikorodu among others.   And God decided to show up, by Femi Adesina     Sen. Uba Sani wins Kaduna APC Gov ticket     Yilwada clinches Plateau APC Gov ticket   He reiterated that the dislodgement was in furtherance of the sanitisation and reform of the red meat value chain. He added that the dislodgement is necessary especially as the state was particular about producing wholesome and healthy meat for its residents. He noted that the team would monitor the existence of illegal slaughter slabs as well as ensure proper regulation of veterinary activities in the state. He said that only the Eko refrigerated meat vans and the Eko live animals transport were permitted to move meat from one place to another. Secretary, Freelance Butchers Association of Nigeria, Seun Omoowo -Olatunji  affirmed support to and compliance with the Lagos State Government’s conditions for healthy meat slaughtering. He expressed his group’s readiness to adopt the state government’s conditions in ensuring healthy red meat consumption.